    {
      "id": "6106651328592812e80b1686278697b8be23320a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-08 07:51:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nhmm, actually I thought we should do swabbing on demand on the client to save cpu cycles on the server.\ncorrect me if i'm wrong...",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b3f9cd683fb970fad897fbf4d072fa89b05ab8a2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-05-08 11:43:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.4/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/b5de0d68-b7d2-11e2-b384-52540035b04c).  Ran 14 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "66c41759166dfd5cdd121046aa4658f8bfda0ed6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-08 15:01:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> hmm, actually I thought we should do swabbing on demand on the client to save cpu cycles on the server. correct me if i'm wrong...\n\nYou are not wrong, but I still hope to convince you on this approach.\n\n1. This has better interoperability. The client /should/ do swabbing on demand. However when a 2.x client swabs LOV xattrs, it does so in a way which assumes that they come over the wire in little-endian. From ll_dir_getstripe():\n\n        /*\n         * This is coming from the MDS, so is probably in\n         * little endian.  We convert it to host endian before\n         * passing it to userspace.\n         */\n        /* We don't swab objects for directories */\n        switch (le32_to_cpu(lmm->lmm_magic)) {\n        case LOV_MAGIC_V1:\n                if (LOV_MAGIC != cpu_to_le32(LOV_MAGIC))\n                        lustre_swab_lov_user_md_v1((struct lov_user_md_v1 *)lmm);\n                break;\n        case LOV_MAGIC_V3:\n                if (LOV_MAGIC != cpu_to_le32(LOV_MAGIC))\n                        lustre_swab_lov_user_md_v3((struct lov_user_md_v3 *)lmm);\n                break;\n        default:\n                CERROR(\"unknown magic: %lX\\n\", (unsigned long)lmm->lmm_magic);\n                rc = -EPROTO;\n        }\n\n2. This is less surprising. For every file or directory other than the root the server will store the LOV EA on disk in little-endian and hence will put it on the wire in that order.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "fd6107ee279df2314f28147d09691fbd4a951eaf",
      "author": {
